<h2 id="qas">Q&amp;As</h2>

<h3 id="calculating-the-concentration-of-110-and-1100-solutions">Calculating the concentration of 1:10 and 1:100 solutions</h3>

<blockquote>
  <p>I think \(V_1\) for stock solutions is 50 mL, but canâ€™t figure out what \(V_1\) is for 1:10 (10 mL ?) and 1:100 dilutions. I want to confirm that \(M_1\) is 1.0 M for all calculations and \(V_2\) is 100 mL. Iâ€™ve looked at the lab procedure and lab video, but get confused about the process of dilutions regarding volumes of \(V_1\).</p>
</blockquote>

<p>As an example, I will walk through the concentration calculations for the  hydrochloric acid dilutions.</p>

<p>The concentration of the stock solution,  \(M_1 = 1.00 \text{ M}\) (letâ€™s use 3 sig. figs.)</p>

<p>where <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">1</code> means initial state. Likewise,  we would use <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">2</code> to indicate the final state.</p>

<h4 id="10-fold-or-110-dilution">10-fold or 1:10 dilution</h4>

<p><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Dilute the solution 10-fold by using a clean, primed, 10 mL volumetric pipette to add 10.00 mL of the stock acid solution to a 100 mL volumetric flask and filling it to the line with deionized water.</code></p>

<p>This means:</p>

<ul>
  <li>\(V_1 = 10.00 \text{ mL}\), which is the amount taken from the stock solution.</li>
  <li>\(V_2 = 100.00 \text{ mL}\), final volume after the dilution.</li>
</ul>

<p>Calculate the concentration of 10-fold dilution as follows.</p>

\[M_1 V_1 = M_2 V_2\]

\[M_1 V_1 = M_2 V_2 \Rightarrow M_2 = \frac{M_1 V_1}{V_2} = \frac{(1.00 \text{ M}) (10.00 \text{ mL})}{100.00 \text{ mL}} = 0.100 \text{ M HCl solution}\]

<h4 id="1100-dilution">1:100 dilution</h4>

<p><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Dilute this solution [i.e. 10-fold diluted colution] another 10-fold by using a 10 mL volumetric pipette to add 10 mL of the 1:10 acid solution to a 100 mL volumetric flask and filling it to the line with deionized water.</code></p>

<p>So, we are using the concentration of 10-fold dilution as the initial concentration for the second 10-fold dilution.</p>

\[M_1 V_1 = M_2 V_2 \Rightarrow M_2 = \frac{M_1 V_1}{V_2} = \frac{(0.100 \text{ M}) (10.00 \text{ mL})}{100.00 \text{ mL}} = 0.0100 \text{ M HCl solution}\]

<h3 id="volumes-in-l-or-ml-for-dilution-calculations">Volumes in L or mL for dilution calculations</h3>

<blockquote>
  <p>I noticed in your sample calculations for the 10 and 100 fold dilutions you used the volumes in mL where molarity is calculated using the units liters. I was wondering if we were to use the volumes in mL as you did in the sample calculations under the Q&amp;Aâ€™s or convert these to the units of liters.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Unit of volume could be mL or L in dilution calculations because the volume units cancel.</p>

